The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Lever weighs price hike
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Lever weighs price hike
          OUR BUREAU                                             
	July 27: Stung by a 1.8 per cent decline in first-quarter net profit, FMCG major Hindustan Unilever is planning to increase the prices of some its products to maintain margins.        
	We are looking at some price changes in the coming quarters. We are planning to increase the prices of a few products to maintain margins...pricing will be up, R. Sridhar, chief financial officer of Hindustan Unilever (HUL), said.         
	He refused to specify the particular categories where product prices would go up.        
	Net profit in the first quarter fell 1.8 per cent to Rs 533.21 crore from Rs 543 crore in the year-ago period. Sridhar attributed the decline to high advertising spends and the hardening of costs of raw materials such as palm oil.        
	However, the overall sales of the company during the quarter rose 7.1 per cent to Rs 4,793 crore from Rs 4,475 crore in the year-ago period.        
	L amp;T profit falls         
	Larsen amp; Toubro (L amp;T) today reported a net profit of Rs 666 crore for the quarter ended June 30, 2010 against Rs 1,598 crore during the same period a year ago.        
	The profit after tax for the corresponding quarter of the previous year at Rs 1,598 crore included an exceptional gain of Rs 1,020 crore from sale of its long-term investment in UltraTech Cement, the company said.        
	Net sales grew 6.4 per cent to Rs 7,835 crore during the April-June quarter.         
	The L amp;T scrip closed at Rs 1,863.25, down 2.94 per cent from its previous close of Rs 1,919.70, on the BSE.        
	OIL net dips         
	Oil India Ltd (OIL) today reported a decline of 32.25 per cent in net profit at Rs 501.11 crore in the June quarter against Rs 739.69 crore in the year-ago period.         
	Total operating income fell to Rs 1,574.15 crore in the quarter from Rs 1,974.61 crore in the same period last year.        
	OIL has allowed a discount of Rs 729.68 crore on the sale of crude oil and LPG for the quarter ended June 2010.                                                                                                                                       
